rticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1111/APM.12884</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">30160021</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Kim K, Ylaya K, Perry C et al (2023) Quality assessment of proteins and RNA following storage in archival formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded human breast cancer tissue microarray sections. Biopreserv Biobank 21:493&#x2013;503. 10.1089/BIO.2022.0090</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1089/BIO.2022.0090</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC10623072</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">36264172</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Sasada S, Takaya M, Suzuki K et al (2026) Differences of HER2 status by HercepTest and PATHWAY 4B5 immunohistochemical assays in breast cancer. Anticancer Res 46:1123&#x2013;1130. 10.21873/ANTICANRES.18015</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.21873/ANTICANRES.18015</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">41617439</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Sakatani T, Tsuda H, Yoshida M et al (2025) Current status and challenges in HER2 IHC assessment: scoring survey results in Japan. Breast Cancer Res Treat 210:27&#x2013;36. 10.1007/S10549-024-07532-2</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1007/S10549-024-07532-2</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC11787237</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">39496910</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Rakha EA, Tan PH, Van Bockstal MR et al (2026) International expert consensus recommendations for HER2 reporting in breast cancer: focus on HER2-low and ultralow categories. Mod Pathol 39:100925. 10.1016/J.MODPAT.2025.100925</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1016/J.MODPAT.2025.100925</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">41167529</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="Publisher" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">42269397</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>10</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">2468-2942</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>48</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Jun</Month><Day>10</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Cancer treatment and research communications</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Cancer Treat Res Commun</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Effectiveness of pegylated liposomal doxorubicin (Caelyx&#xae;) monotherapy in patients with metastatic HER2-low breast cancer: a monocentric retrospective study.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>101276</StartPage><MedlinePgn>101276</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.ctarc.2026.101276</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S2468-2942(26)00187-5</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="CONTEXT" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Breast cancer (BC) is the most common cancer worldwide, and anthracyclines remain a key component of systemic therapy despite expanding treatment options. A refined HER2 classification has recently emerged, distinguishing HER2-negative (IHC score 0), HER2-low, and HER2-positive tumors. While HER2-low status predicts response to trastuzumab-deruxtecan, its biological significance remains uncertain. Anthracyclines have shown superior activity in HER2-positive BC, potentially through ERBB2/TOP2A co-amplification, but their effectiveness in HER2-low tumors has not been evaluated. This study assessed whether HER2-low status predicts anthracycline benefit in metastatic BC.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">We conducted a single-center retrospective study including 114 patients with HER2-negative or HER2-low metastatic BC treated with pegylated liposomal doxorubicin (PLD) between 2013 and 2021. The primary endpoint was real-world progression-free survival (rwPFS).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Median rwPFS was 2.6 months (95% CI, 2.1-3.2) in HER2-low disease and 3.1 months (95% CI, 2.3-3.8) in HER2 score 0 disease, with no statistically significant difference. In multivariable analysis, HER2-low status was not independently associated with rwPFS.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">PLD demonstrated modest efficacy in metastatic BC lacking HER2 overexpression, with comparable outcomes in HER2-low and HER2-negative subgroups. These findings suggest that HER2-low status does not predict anthracycline benefit and support the view that HER2-low is unlikely to represent a distinct therapeutic subtype. Further research is needed to refine treatment selection in this heterogeneous population.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 The Authors. Published by Elsevier Ltd.. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Boudier</LastName><ForeName>Philippe</ForeName><Initials>P</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Institut Public de Canc&#xe9;rologie Strauss Europe, 17 rue Albert Calmette, 67200 Strasbourg, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bischoff</LastName><ForeName>Herv&#xe9;</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Institut Public de Canc&#xe9;rologie Strauss Europe, 17 rue Albert Calmette, 67200 Strasbourg, France. Electronic address: h.bischoff@institut-strauss.fr.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Somme</LastName><ForeName>Laura</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Institut Public de Canc&#xe9;rologie Strauss Europe, 17 rue Albert Calmette, 67200 Strasbourg, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Pflumio</LastName><ForeName>Carole</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Institut Public de Canc&#xe9;rologie Strauss Europe, 17 rue Albert Calmette, 67200 Strasbourg, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kalish</LastName><ForeName>Michal</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Institut Public de Canc&#xe9;rologie Strauss Europe, 17 rue Albert Calmette, 67200 Strasbourg, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Fischbach</LastName><ForeName>Cathie</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Institut Public de Canc&#xe9;rologie Strauss Europe, 17 rue Albert Calmette, 67200 Strasbourg, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Velten</LastName><ForeName>Michel</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Public Health, Institut Public de Canc&#xe9;rologie Strauss Europe, 17 rue Albert Calmette, 67200 Strasbourg, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Petit</LastName><ForeName>Thierry</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Institut Public de Canc&#xe9;rologie Strauss Europe, 17 rue Albert Calmette, 67200 Strasbourg, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>10</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>England</Country><MedlineTA>Cancer Treat Res Commun</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>101694651</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>2468-2942</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><KeywordList Owner="NOTNLM"><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Breast cancer</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">HER2low</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Pegylated liposomal doxorubicin</Keyword></KeywordList><CoiStatement>Declaration of competing interest The authors declare no conflicts of interest in relation to the publication of this manuscript.</CoiStatement></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="received"><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>23</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="revised"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>1</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="accepted"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>23</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>11</Day><Hour>5</Hour><Minute>42</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>11</Day><Hour>5</Hour><Minute>42</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>10</Day><Hour>18</Hour><Minute>7</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>aheadofprint</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">42269397</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1016/j.ctarc.2026.101276</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pii">S2468-2942(26)00187-5</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="PubMed-not-MEDLINE" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">42254250</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>08</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>08</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic-eCollection"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">2049-0801</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><Volume>88</Volume><Issue>6</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Jun</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Annals of medicine and surgery (2012)</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Ann Med Surg (Lond)</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Next-generation antibody-drug conjugates in drug-resistant solid tumors: promise, toxicity, and the emerging challenge of acquired resistance.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>3861</StartPage><EndPage>3863</EndPage><MedlinePgn>3861-3863</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1097/MS9.0000000000004933</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Drug-resistant solid tumors represent a major challenge in oncology, with resistance mechanisms, including efflux pump overexpression, apoptotic pathway alterations, and adaptive survival signaling, contributing to poor outcomes despite multimodal therapy. Conventional chemotherapy and first-generation antibody-drug conjugates (ADCs), such as ado-trastuzumab emtansine (T-DM1), were limited by non-specific cytotoxicity, heterogeneous drug-antibody ratios, linker instability, and insufficient bystander killing, yielding modest efficacy in heavily pretreated populations. Next-generation ADCs address these shortcomings through site-specific conjugation, advanced cleavable linkers, and novel payloads, such as topoisomerase I inhibitors, enabling robust bystander killing and circumvention of efflux-mediated resistance. Clinically, trastuzumab deruxtecan demonstrated meaningful progression-free survival benefit in HER2-low metastatic breast cancer, while enfortumab vedotin reduced mortality risk in platinum- and immunotherapy-refractory urothelial carcinoma, establishing ADC efficacy across solid tumor histologies. However, significant toxicity concerns persist. Trastuzumab deruxtecan carries a 15.4% incidence of interstitial lung disease, including fatal events, and sacituzumab govitecan is associated with grade 3 or higher neutropenia in approximately 51% of patients. Furthermore, next-generation ADCs are not resistance-proof, with antigen downregulation, payload efflux, and impaired internalization emerging as clinically relevant escape mechanisms. Biomarker-driven patient selection, rigorous toxicity monitoring, and prospective trials addressing resistance will be essential to realizing the full and durable potential of this drug class.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 The Author(s). Published by Wolters Kluwer Health, Inc.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Khan</LastName><ForeName>Sarum Ali</ForeName><Initials>SA</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0005-3980-2398</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medicine, Wah Medical College, Wah Cantt, Pakistan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ali</LastName><ForeName>Taimoor</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0009-8003-6866</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medicine, Wah Medical College, Wah Cantt, Pakistan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Khan</LastName><ForeName>Aleeza</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0005-8706-9506</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medicine, Nishtar Medical College, Nishtar Medical University, Multan, Pakistan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hameed</LastName><ForeName>Aneeza</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0001-9282-778X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medicine, Wah Medical College, Wah Cantt, Pakistan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Tahir</LastName><ForeName>Aiman</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medicine, Azad Jammu and Kashmir Medical College, Muzaffarabad, AJK, Pakistan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Qamar</LastName><ForeName>Muhammad Adnan</ForeName><Initials>MA</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0004-9615-0915</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Internal Medicine, Spinghar Medical University, Kabul, Afghanistan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016422">Letter</PublicationTyp