nce><Citation>Sung H, Ferlay J, Siegel RL, et al. Global cancer statistics 2020: GLOBOCAN estimates of incidence and mortality worldwide for 36 cancers in 185 countries. CA Cancer J Clin 2021;71:209&#x2013;49.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">33538338</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Vasan N, Baselga J, Hyman DM. A view on drug resistance in cancer. Nature 2019;575:299&#x2013;309.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC8008476</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">31723286</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Criscitiello C, Morganti S, Curigliano G. Antibody-drug conjugates in solid tumors: a look into novel targets. J Hematol Oncol 2021;14:20.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC7844898</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">33509252</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Gottesman MM, Fojo T, Bates SE. Multidrug resistance in cancer: role of ATP-dependent transporters. Nat Rev Cancer 2002;2:48&#x2013;58.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">11902585</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Lambert JM, Chari RV. Ado-trastuzumab emtansine (T-DM1): an antibody-drug conjugate for HER2-positive breast cancer. J Med Chem 2014;57:6949&#x2013;64.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">24967516</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Drago JZ, Modi S, Chandarlapaty S. Unlocking the potential of antibody-drug conjugates for cancer therapy. Nat Rev Clin Oncol 2021;18:327&#x2013;44.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC8287784</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">33558752</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Verma S, Miles D, Gianni L, et al. Trastuzumab emtansine for HER2-positive advanced breast cancer. N Engl J Med 2012;367:1783&#x2013;91.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC5125250</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">23020162</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Rugo HS, Jacot W, Tokunaga E, et al. Trastuzumab deruxtecan vs treatment of physician&#x2019;s choice in HER2-low metastatic breast cancer: subgroup analyses from DESTINY-Breast06. Cancer Res 2025;85:GS01&#x2013;10.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>Powles T, Rosenberg JE, Sonpavde GP, et al. Enfortumab vedotin in previously treated advanced urothelial carcinoma. N Engl J Med 2021;384:1125&#x2013;35.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC8450892</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">33577729</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Bardia A, Messersmith WA, Krop IE, et al. Sacituzumab govitecan in metastatic triple-negative breast cancer. N Engl J Med 2021;384:1529&#x2013;41.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">33882206</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Powell CA, Modi S, Iwata H, et al. Pooled analysis of drug-related interstitial lung disease and/or pneumonitis in nine trastuzumab deruxtecan monotherapy studies. ESMO Open 2022;7:100554.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC9434416</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">35963179</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Teo MY, Rosenberg JE. NECTIN4 heterogeneity and molecular diversity in bladder cancers: deconstructing the activity of an antibody-drug conjugate. Clin Cancer Res 2021;27:4950&#x2013;52.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">34281911</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Noriega HA, Halilovic E, Charlab R, et al. AI-driven innovation in antibody-drug conjugate design. Front Drug Discov 2025;5:1628789.</Citation></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="Publisher" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">42204863</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>28</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1542-6270</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>May</Month><Day>27</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>The Annals of pharmacotherapy</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Ann Pharmacother</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Difference in Cost-Effectiveness of Trastuzumab Deruxtecan in First-Line Versus Later-Line Settings for HER2-Low Metastatic Breast Cancer.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>10600280261447399</StartPage><MedlinePgn>10600280261447399</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1177/10600280261447399</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Trastuzumab deruxtecan (T-DXd) is approved as first-line therapy for HER2-low metastatic breast cancer after endocrine therapy failure and as later-line therapy, but economic evidence comparing these two settings to inform sequencing decisions is lacking.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">To compare the cost-effectiveness of T-DXd between first-line and later-line settings for HER2-low metastatic breast cancer from a Japanese healthcare payer perspective.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">A partitioned survival model was developed using data from the DESTINY-Breast06 and DESTINY-Breast04 trials. The analysis adopted a Japanese healthcare payer perspective with a 30-year time horizon and 2% annual discounting for both costs and outcomes. Incremental cost-effectiveness ratios (ICERs) were compared against a willingness-to-pay threshold of 15 million JPY per quality-adjusted life-year (QALY). Deterministic, probabilistic, and scenario sensitivity analyses were conducted.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">T-DXd yielded an ICER of 37.36 million JPY/QALY in the first-line setting and 63.29 million JPY/QALY in the later-line setting compared with physician's choice chemotherapy. Sensitivity analyses confirmed the robustness of these estimates, with first-line T-DXd consistently more favourable across scenarios.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION AND RELEVANCE" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">T-DXd exceeded the willingness-to-pay threshold in both settings at current pricing, indicating it was not cost-effective. Although the first-line ICER was approximately 40% lower than the later-line ICER, achieving cost-effectiveness in the first-line setting requires a larger proportional price reduction because the comparator chemotherapy in that setting is less expensive. This first Japanese cost-effectiveness analysis directly comparing the two settings should inform pricing negotiations and highlight the need for predictive biomarkers of the T-DXd response.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kashiwa</LastName><ForeName>Munenobu</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-5178-611X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Comprehensive Unit for Health Economic Evidence Review and Decision Support (CHEERS), Research Organization of Science and Technology, Ritsumeikan University, Kusatsu, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Fujimori</LastName><ForeName>Maya</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Laboratory of Clinical Pharmacy and Healthcare Science, Institute of Medical, Pharmaceutical and Health Sciences, Kanazawa University, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>27</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Ann Pharmacother</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>9203131</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>1060-0280</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><KeywordList Owner="NOTNLM"><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">breast cancer</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">chemotherapy</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">cost-effectiveness</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">pharmacoeconomics</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">trastuzumab deruxtecan</Keyword></KeywordList></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>28</Day><Hour>6</Hour><Minute>32</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>28</Day><Hour>6</Hour><Minute>32</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>28</Day><Hour>2</Hour><Minute>22</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>aheadofprint</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">42204863</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1177/10600280261447399</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="PubMed-not-MEDLINE" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">42170576</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>22</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>22</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic-eCollection"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">2218-6778</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>7</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Translational breast cancer research : a journal focusing on translational research in breast cancer</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Transl Breast Cancer Res</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Efficacy and safety of T-DXd in patients with HER2-positive and HER2-low metastatic breast cancer: a real-world study.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>12</StartPage><MedlinePgn>12</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">12</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.21037/tbcr-25-53</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">The DESTINY-Breast trials established trastuzumab deruxtecan (T-DXd) as a treatment significantly improving outcomes in human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2)-positive and HER2-low metastatic breast cancer (MBC). However, real-world effectiveness is susceptible to confounding factors. This multicenter, real-world study aims to systematically evaluate the efficacy and safety of T-DXd in patients with HER2-positive and HER2-low MBC. Key clinicopathological parameters were to be integrated to develop an individualized prognostic prediction model, facilitating precision medicine implementation in clinical practice.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">A retrospective analysis was conducted on clinical data from 142 patients with advanced breast cancer who received T-DXd therapy at multiple centers in Jiangsu and Anhui provinces between January 1, 2021, and August 31, 2024. The primary endpoints were progression-free survival (PFS), objective response rate (ORR), disease control rate (DCR), and the incidence of adverse events (AEs). Univariate and multivariate Cox proportional hazards regression analyses were utilized to identify clinicopathological variables significantly associated with clinical outcomes and to develop a dynamic risk prediction model. Model performance was evaluated using the area under the receiver operating characteristic curve (AUC) to assess discriminative ability, Bootstrap calibration curves to determine predictive accuracy, and K-fold cross-validation to examine model stability and reproducibility.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">The median PFS in the total population was 9.5 months [95% confidence interval (CI): 7.2-11.9], with ORR and DCR of 30.3% and 88.7%, respectively. Subgroup analysis revealed significantly longer median PFS in HER2-positive patients compared to HER2-low patients (12.5 <i>vs.</i> 8.1 months, P=0.02) and superior efficacy with frontline (1<sup>st</sup>-2<sup>nd</sup> line) <i>vs.</i> later-line therapy (12.0 <i>vs.</i> 8.3 months, P=0.041). Additionally, dose reduction (98/142, 69.0%) did not significantly impact PFS overall (P=0.74) or in HER2 subgroups (positive: P=0.77; low: P=0.23). Based on the results of Cox analysis, this study established a nomogram model providing visual risk prediction [concordance index (C-index) =0.65, AUC =0.760] to achieve individualized prognostic visualization assessment and assist in clinical decision-making for T-DXd treatment. In this study, hematological AEs were most common (leukopenia: 56.3%, anemia: 69.0%). Non-hematological reactions included fatigue (46.5%) and hepatic dysfunction (40.1%), etc. The incidence of interstitial lung disease (ILD) was 4.9%, and all were mild cases.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">Real-world evidence confirms T-DXd maintains clinical trial-aligned efficacy and safety. Earlier-line administration enhances survival benefit, while efficacy is preserved with dose reduction and remains acceptable in patients with limited physical capacity. Neutropenia and anemia predominated as hematologic toxicities; ILD incidence was lower than internationally reported. Key prognostic factors were integrated into a predictive model demonstrating good discrimination, stability, and consistency, supporting individualized treatment decisions.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; AME Publishing Company.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y" EqualContrib="Y"><LastName>Lu</LastName><ForeName>Rongrong</ForeName><Initials>R</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Oncology, The First Affiliated Hospital of Nanjing Medical University, Nanjing, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>The First Clinical College of Nanjing Medical University, Nanjing, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y" EqualContrib="Y"><Last